{"title_page": "Peter Schmeichel", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Peter Schmeichel<br/><small>[[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]</small>\n| image          = Peter Schmeichel 2012-01-25 001.jpg\n| caption        = Schmeichel in 2012\n| fullname       = Peter Boles\u0142aw Schmeichel\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1963|11|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Gladsaxe Municipality|Gladsaxe]], Denmark\n| height         = 1.91 m<ref>[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/1554 Peter Schmeichel]. [[Danish Football Association|DBU]]. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref>\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1    = 1972\u20131975 |youthclubs1 = H\u00f8je-Gladsaxe\n| youthyears2    = 1975\u20131979 |youthclubs2 = [[BK Hero|Hero]]\n| youthyears3    = 1979\u20131981 |youthclubs3 = [[Gladsaxe-Hero BK|Gladsaxe-Hero]]\n| years1         = 1981\u20131984 |clubs1 = [[Gladsaxe-Hero BK|Gladsaxe-Hero]]           |caps1 = 46  |goals1 = 0\n| years2         = 1984\u20131987 |clubs2 = [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]]                     |caps2 = 78  |goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 1987\u20131991 |clubs3 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]                       |caps3 = 119 |goals3 = 2\n| years4         = 1991\u20131999 |clubs4 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] |caps4 = 292 |goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 1999\u20132001 |clubs5 = [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]]   |caps5 = 55  |goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 2001\u20132002 |clubs6 = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]             |caps6 = 29  |goals6 = 1\n| years7         = 2002\u20132003 |clubs7 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]     |caps7 = 29  |goals7 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 648 |totalgoals = 3<!-- LEAGUE ONLY -->\n| nationalyears1 = 1987\u20132001 |nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] |nationalcaps1 = 129 |nationalgoals1 = 1\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|DEN}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[UEFA Euro 1992|1992 Sweden]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Peter Boles\u0142aw Schmeichel''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] ({{IPA-da|\u02c8p\u02b0e\u031d\u02c0t\u0250 \u02c8smaj\u02c0kl\u0329}}; born 18 November 1963) is a Danish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], and was voted the [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper]] in 1992 and 1993. He is best remembered for his most successful years at English club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], whom he [[Captain (association football)|captained]] to victory in the [[1999 UEFA Champions League Final]] to complete [[Treble (association football)|the Treble]], and for winning [[UEFA Euro 1992]] with [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].\n\nBorn in [[Gladsaxe Municipality|Gladsaxe]], [[Copenhagen]], Schmeichel was famous for his intimidating physique\u2009\u2013\u2009at {{height|m=1.91}} tall and weighing close to {{convert|100|kg|stlb|abbr=on}} during his playing days\u2009\u2013\u2009and wore specially made size XXXL football shirts.<ref name=\"Red11\">{{cite web |title=Peter Schmeichel |url=http://www.red11.org/mufc/peter.htm |publisher=Red11.org |year=1999 |accessdate=4 November 2013 }}</ref> A fierce competitor, he was known for his loud, unstinting criticism of perceived mistakes by his defenders.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2zI4AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT244|title=Manchester United: The Biography: The Complete Story of the World's Greatest Football Club|first=Jim|last=White|date=7 October 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|accessdate=4 January 2020|via=Google Books}}</ref> Unusually for a goalkeeper, Schmeichel scored 10 goals during his career, including one for the national team. He is also the most [[cap (football)|capped]] player for the Denmark national team, with 129 games between 1987 and 2001. In addition to Euro 92, he played for his country at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] and three additional [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]] tournaments. He captained the national team in 30 matches. He also represented Gladsaxe Hero, [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]], [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]], [[Sporting CP]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in a career that lasted from 1981 until 2003 and yielded 24 trophies.\n\nRegarded as one of the greatest goalkeepers of all-time, the [[IFFHS]] ranked Schmeichel among the top ten [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper#Goalkeeper of the Century|keepers of the 20th century]] in 2000,<ref name=\"IFFHS' Century Elections\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/iffhs-century.html#worldkoc |title=IFFHS' Century Elections |accessdate=21 June 2007 |first=Karel |last=Stokkermans |date=30 January 2000 |work=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] }}</ref> and in 2001, Schmeichel won a public poll held by [[Reuters]], when the majority of the 200,000 participants voted him as the best goalkeeper ever, ahead of [[Lev Yashin]] and [[Gordon Banks]].<ref name=\"showstars\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showstars.dk/query:invoke/method:display/folderid:3216/lang:da/ |title=PETER SCHMEICHEL |accessdate=21 June 2007 |work=ShowStars.dk |language=Danish |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704194758/http://www.showstars.dk/query:invoke/method:display/folderid:3216/lang:da/ |archivedate=4 July 2007}}</ref> In 2003, Schmeichel was inducted into the [[English Football Hall of Fame]] in recognition of his impact on the English game. In March 2004, he was named as one of the \"125 greatest living footballers\", at the [[FIFA 100]] celebrations. His son, [[Kasper Schmeichel|Kasper]], is also a professional goalkeeper, currently playing for Premier League side [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early years===\nPeter Schmeichel was born in the [[S\u00f8borgg\u00e5rd]] parish of [[Gladsaxe Municipality|Gladsaxe]], Denmark, to Inger, a Danish nurse, and Antoni Schmeichel, a [[Polish people|Polish]] jazz musician. He held Polish [[citizen]]ship until 1970 when he, his father, and his three sisters became Danish citizens.\n\nSchmeichel inherited his middle name \u2013 Boles\u0142aw \u2013 from his great-grandfather.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), p. 25</ref> He spent his early years in the town of [[Buddinge]], [[Copenhagen]], and began his football career playing for a team in the adjacent suburb of [[H\u00f8je-Gladsaxe]]. His first match came on 7 August 1972 at the age of 8.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), p. 29</ref> After a two-and-a-half-year unbeaten run, Schmeichel was approached by BK Hero, a team from a few divisions above H\u00f8je-Gladsaxe and with one of the largest youth football schemes in Denmark. BK Hero merged with Gladsaxe BK in 1979 to form [[Gladsaxe-Hero BK]], and Schmeichel was presented with the opportunity to play for the [[Zealand Football Association|Zealand FA's]] junior representative team.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 30\u201331</ref>\n\nEventually graduating to the Gladsaxe-Hero senior squad, Schmeichel met his first mentor in [[Svend Aage Hansen]], the first team coach at the club, and later to become his father-in-law. With Gladsaxe-Hero already relegated from the Danish Third Division with three games to go, Hansen promoted Schmeichel and six others from the youth team for a match against [[IF Skjold Birker\u00f8d]]. The team lost 1\u20130, but Schmeichel received mentions in local newspapers for his personal performance.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), p. 31</ref> At the end of the season, Hansen explained to Schmeichel his plan for the future, which involved Schmeichel spending two more seasons with Gladsaxe-Hero BK before moving on to [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]], playing for the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]], and eventually having a successful career abroad. Schmeichel admits that he had received an offer to play for [[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]]'s youth team, but he turned it down as the club \"seemed a bit boring\".<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 31\u201332</ref>\n\nThe following season Gladsaxe-Hero needed only to avoid defeat to Stubbek\u00f8bing to prevent relegation from the Danish National League. In the end, Schmeichel played one of the best games of his career and Gladsaxe-Hero won the match. At the end of the game, Hansen's daughter, Bente, ran onto the pitch and hugged Schmeichel. The two ended up going out as a couple, and they eventually got married.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 32\u201333</ref>\n\nBefore becoming a professional footballer, Schmeichel had to work a number of jobs to make ends meet. His first job came in the dyeing department of a textile factory, but safety concerns led to his resignation. He then spent 12 months as a cleaner at an old people's home, before taking up an office job with the [[World Wide Fund for Nature|World Wildlife Fund]]. He originally worked in the organisation's shops, but three weeks after he joined, the store manager left and Schmeichel was promoted to the position of sales manager. Soon after, Schmeichel was called upon to do his four weeks of compulsory military service. However, this coincided with Hvidovre's summer training camp in Portugal, which he was permitted to go on with the proviso that he completed his military service the following month. Nevertheless, the delicate organisational situation that arose between the WWF, the Danish defence department and Hvidovre prompted Schmeichel to give up working for the WWF. A job with his father-in-law's flooring firm came next, until he realised that his knees could not support his {{convert|15|stone|kg}} frame for eight hours a day, and he was offered a job with the advertising firm owned by Hvidovre's chairman, Niels Erik Madsen. This was to be his last job outside football, as he was offered a contract with [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]] the following spring.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 34\u201337</ref>\n\n===Professional career===\n\n====Br\u00f8ndby (1987\u20131991)====\nDespite the fifth best defence in the league, conceding 40 goals in 30 games,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home6.inet.tele.dk/pin/Danmarksturneringen/1985.htm |title=Danmarksturneringen 1985 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |first=Peder I. |last=Nielsen |year=1999 |publisher=Peders Fodboldstatistik |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316190707/http://home6.inet.tele.dk/pin/Danmarksturneringen/1985.htm |archivedate=16 March 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Schmeichel and Hvidovre finished in 14th place and were [[relegated]] in 1985. After only a single season, the club bounced right back to the 1st Division, but Schmeichel was lost by Hvidovre to Danish runners-up [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] before the 1987 season. Winning the Danish league in his first year, he joined a club which he helped turn into a success. He made his debut for the Danish national team in May 1987, under national manager [[Sepp Piontek]], and was selected for the [[1988 UEFA European Football Championship|Euro 88]] tournament, where he eventually became Denmark's starting goalkeeper, after initially serving as a back-up to [[Troels Rasmussen]] in Denmark's opening 3\u20132 defeat to [[Spain national football team|Spain]]; Denmark lost both of their remaining two matches 2\u20130 to [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] and [[Italy national football team|Italy]], however, and were eliminated in the first round of the competition.<ref name=\"Honours\"/>\n\nIn all, Schmeichel and Br\u00f8ndby won four championships in five seasons. The climax of his Br\u00f8ndby career would come in the European 1991 [[UEFA Cup]] competition, which saw Schmeichel as an important part of the team that reached the semi-finals, keeping seven clean sheets in the competition.<ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref name=\"Denmark's fairytale\">{{cite web|title=Euro 1992: Denmark's fairytale|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/17757335|publisher=BBC Sport|author1=Saj Chowdhury|date=12 May 2012|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> The club was eliminated from the tournament following a 2\u20131 away defeat to [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] with a last-minute goal by [[Rudi V\u00f6ller]].<ref name=\"Honours\"/> Following the tournament, Schmeichel was voted 10th in \"The World's Best Goalkeeper 1991\" poll by the [[IFFHS]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iffhs.de/?388d85ff8b00388f05e9d817285fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb8a70b |title=The World's best Goalkeeper 1991 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |publisher=IFFHS }}</ref>\n\n====Manchester United (1991\u20131999)====\n[[File:Peter Schmeichel juli 1991.JPG|thumb|Schmeichel in July 1991, just days after signing for Manchester United]]\nFollowing his showings on the international scene, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] signed Schmeichel on 6 August 1991 for \u00a3505,000,<ref>Br\u00f8ndby \u00abtabte\u00bb p\u00e5 Schmeichel, ''[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] article'', 8 August 1991</ref> a price described in 2000 by Manchester United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] as the \"bargain of the century.\"<ref name=\"mbe\">{{cite news |title=Schmeichel's MBE honour |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/1092672.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=30 December 2000 |accessdate=21 June 2007 }}</ref> It was mainly because at the time, Schmeichel was a relative unknown outside Denmark, especially within the United squad members. Schmeichel played the bulk of his career for United, eight years in total. With United, Schmeichel won five FA Premier League titles, three FA Cups, one [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], and the UEFA Champions League.\n\nManchester United finished as runners-up in Schmeichel's first season (also winning the [[Football League Cup]] for the first time in the club's history), but it was on the international stage that Schmeichel enjoyed his biggest success that year. In the Danish national team under new national manager [[Richard M\u00f8ller Nielsen]], Schmeichel was Denmark's starting goalkeeper at the [[UEFA Euro 1992|Euro 92]] tournament which they won.<ref name=\"Denmark's fairytale\"/> Although Denmark initially finished behind [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]] in their qualification campaign for the final tournament, the latter nation were banned from the competition, while Denmark replaced them in the finals.<ref name=\"Honours\"/> Schmeichel made a string of important saves during the tournament,<ref name=\"Denmark's fairytale\"/> keeping a clean sheet in Denmark's opening 0\u20130 draw against [[England national football team|England]], and producing decisive stops against [[Eric Cantona]] and [[Jean-Pierre Papin]] in a 2\u20131 win over [[France national football team|France]] to advance to the last four.<ref name=\"Honours\"/> In the semi-finals against defending champions the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], following a 2\u20132 draw after extra time, he stopped a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] from [[Marco van Basten]] \u2013 the only miss of the shoot-out \u2013 which enabled Denmark to advance to the [[UEFA Euro 1992 Final|final]] on a 5\u20134 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/24/news/24iht-bast_0.html|title=The Score From a $6 Million Soccer Star: 'Someone Had to Miss'|publisher=The New York Times|author1=Rob Hughes|date=24 June 1992|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> Schmeichel also made several decisive saves in the final, and even held a cross with one hand, keeping a clean sheet in his nation's 2\u20130 victory over Germany.<ref name=\"Schmeichel steps back in time\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1992/history-maker/index.html|title=Schmeichel steps back in time to EURO '92|publisher=UEFA.com|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1992/matches/round=217/match=6098/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Gatecrashing Denmark down Germany|publisher=UEFA.com|date=5 October 2003|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> For his performances throughout the season, he was elected \"The World's Best Goalkeeper of 1992\" by IFFHS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iffhs.de/?388d85ff8b00388f05e9d817285fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb8a40b |title=The World's best Goalkeeper 1992 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |publisher=[[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]] }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393 season]], 22 [[clean sheet]]s from Schmeichel helped United win the [[Premier League]] championship, the first time the club had won England's top trophy in 26 years.<ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref name=\"The Great Dane\">{{cite web|url=https://www.unitedlounge.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=9775 |title=Schmeichel: The Great Dane|publisher=United Lounge|author1=Tom Adams|date=28 August 2009}}</ref> Schmeichel was once again named \"The World's Best Goalkeeper\" in 1993. In January 1994, Schmeichel fell out with Ferguson, as United had squandered a 3\u20130 lead to draw 3\u20133 with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. The two had a row where Schmeichel \"said the most horrible things\",<ref>\"[...] sagde de frygteligste ting.\", Schmeichel (2000), p. 143</ref> and he was subsequently sacked by Ferguson. A few days later, Schmeichel made an improvised apology to the other players. Unknown to him, Ferguson was eavesdropping on this, and he let Schmeichel stay at Manchester United.<ref name=\"mbe\"/> Schmeichel and United repeated the Premier League championship win at the end of the season, also capturing the [[FA Cup]].<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/> At international level, however, he suffered disappointment as Denmark failed to qualify for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"Honours\"/>\n\nSchmeichel played for Denmark at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]], hosted by England. The defending European Champions went out in the preliminary group stage, despite delivering results equivalent to the Euro 92 tournament in the first round.<ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref>One victory, one draw, and one loss in three group stage matches.</ref>\n\nFollowing a match against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in November 1996, Schmeichel was accused of [[racism]] by Arsenal striker [[Ian Wright]]. During the game, Schmeichel and Wright had a number of controversies, and at the end of the game, the two players confronted each other on their way off the pitch. After the game, news emerged of a police inquiry into the incident, where it was alleged that Schmeichel had made a racist remark.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rob |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/schmeichel-faces-racist-abuse-charge-1279851.html |title=Schmeichel faces racist abuse charge |work=The Independent |date=21 February 1997 |accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref> After months of politicising by [[The FA]] and [[The PFA]], who wanted a \"converted\" Schmeichel as their posterboy of the \"Kick Racism out of Football\" campaign, no evidence was found and the case was dropped.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 123\u2013133</ref>\n\nUnder new national manager [[Bo Johansson]], Schmeichel was a part of the Danish squad at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He was one of the leading members of the Danish campaign, which ended in a 3\u20132 quarter-final defeat to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref name=\"Honours\"/>\n\nSchmeichel ended his Manchester United career on [[Manchester United F.C. season 1998\u201399|the highest note]], when Schmeichel and United won [[the Treble]], the FA Premier League title, [[FA Cup]] and UEFA Champions League, in the same season. In that year's FA Cup semi-final against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], Schmeichel saved a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] by [[Dennis Bergkamp]] in the last minutes of the game (which Schmeichel revealed he was unaware of time), to send the game into extra time.<ref name=\"Honours\"/> In the absence of the suspended [[Roy Keane]], he captained United in the [[UEFA Champions League]] final in May 1999. German opponents [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] had a 1\u20130 lead until the dying minutes of the game, when United received a corner kick. Schmeichel ran into the attack attempting to cause confusion, and [[Teddy Sheringham]] scored the equalising goal. A few seconds later, [[Ole Gunnar Solskj\u00e6r]] scored the 2\u20131 winner for United to ensure that Schmeichel's United career ended on the highest possible note.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1468092.html|title=Schmeichel recalls 1999 marvel|publisher=UEFA.com|date=29 March 2010|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> In an unforgettable celebratory moment, Schmeichel was shown cartwheeling gleefully in his area after Solskj\u00e6r's winning goal.<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/>\n\nWith his departure, Manchester United had trouble finding a replacement for him, going through several high-profile goalkeepers including [[Mark Bosnich]], [[Massimo Taibi]], [[Fabien Barthez]], [[Tim Howard]] and [[Roy Carroll]] before finally buying [[Edwin van der Sar]], who Sir Alex Ferguson considered the best goalkeeper to have played for the club since Schmeichel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=396279&&cc=3888 |title=Van der Sar pens new one-year deal at United |work=[[ESPN Soccernet]] |date=15 December 2006 |accessdate=20 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nSchmeichel played his 129th and last international against Slovenia in 2001. He kept a clean sheet in the match \u2013 something he had done, staggeringly, in 42 per cent of his appearances for Manchester United. Schmeichel will be remembered as far more than being the greatest goalie in the history of De R\u00f8d-Hvide and the Red Devils. Indeed, in a 2001 Reuters poll, he beat Lev Yashin and Gordon Banks to be named the finest keeper in football history. Despite being a goalkeeper, he would run into the attack on corner kicks if his team was behind. The sight of him going up for the corner was a great distraction to opposing defenders. He scored a goal in this fashion, for Man United, in a [[1995\u201396 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] match against [[Rotor Volgograd]] at Old Trafford in September 1995. He scored in the last minutes of the game to tie the match 2\u20132, though United were eliminated from the tournament on the away goals rule.<ref name=\"Europe's goalscoring goalkeepers\"/>\n\n====Sporting CP (1999\u20132001)====\nSchmeichel decided to leave English football at the end of the 1998\u201399 season, as the gruelling 60-game season, which came with playing with a successful club, was threatening to undermine his high standards at the age of 36. Seeking a slower pace of football, he moved to [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]], where he penned a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-Man United keeper Schmeichel signs with Sporting Lisbon |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=ex-man-united-keeper-schmeichel-signs-with-sporting-lisbon-1999-06-22 |work=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=22 June 1999 |accessdate=5 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205055233/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=ex-man-united-keeper-schmeichel-signs-with-sporting-lisbon-1999-06-22 |archive-date=5 February 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his first season with the club, he won the [[1999\u20132000 Primeira Liga]] title, putting an end to the team's 18 years without a championship. He scored his only goal for the Danish national team, a penalty kick in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], in a June 2000 warm-up match for [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]].<ref name=\"Europe's goalscoring goalkeepers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2009682.html|title=Europe's goalscoring goalkeepers|publisher=UEFA.com|date=9 July 2014|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> He represented Denmark at Euro 2000, where the team was eliminated in the group stage. He announced his retirement from the national team in February 2001,<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel calls time on Denmark |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/football/europe/newsid_1180000/1180695.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 February 2001 |accessdate=2 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010717145503/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/football/europe/newsid_1180000/1180695.stm |archivedate=17 July 2001 }}</ref> and played his final match (his 129th international appearance)<ref name=\"Honours\"/> two months later, captaining the side in a 3\u20130 friendly win over [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] at Copenhagen's [[Parken Stadium]]; he was substituted in the 65th minute to a standing ovation, replaced by long-time back-up [[Peter Kj\u00e6r (footballer)|Peter Kj\u00e6r]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel bows out |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/2001/04/25/denmark_slovenia/ |work=CNNSI.com |publisher=CNN/Sports Illustrated |date=25 April 2001 |accessdate=2 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103231945/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/2001/04/25/denmark_slovenia/ |archive-date=3 November 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHis second year with Sporting was remarkable in that it was the first time in 14 years, since his Hvidovre days, that Schmeichel's club had finished below second place in the league. Schmeichel stated his wish to activate a contract option of a further year at Sporting in January 2001,<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel staying at Sporting |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1114009.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=12 January 2001 |accessdate=2 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010820055107/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/football/europe/newsid_1114000/1114009.stm |archivedate=20 August 2001 }}</ref> but eventually decided to leave the club when his contract expired in June 2001.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel leaves Sporting Lisbon |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1391019.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=15 June 2001 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113032429/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1391019.stm |archivedate=13 January 2009 }}</ref>\n\n====Aston Villa (2001\u20132002)====\nSchmeichel returned to England with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in July 2001, signing a one-year contract with the option to extend it by a further year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Villa clinch Schmeichel deal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/1435755.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=12 July 2001 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030418154533/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/1435755.stm |archivedate=18 April 2003 }}</ref> On 20 October 2001, Schmeichel became the first goalkeeper to score a Premier League goal, in a 3\u20132 defeat away to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]];<ref name=\"Honours\"/> this feat has been repeated only four times: by [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]' [[Brad Friedel]] on 21 February 2004, also from a corner kick; by [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]'s [[Paul Robinson (goalkeeper)|Paul Robinson]] from a free-kick on 17 March 2007; by Everton's [[Tim Howard]] on 4 January 2012; and by [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]'s [[Asmir Begovi\u0107]] on 2 November 2013.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=McKenna |title=Stoke 1\u20131 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24681360 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 November 2013 |accessdate=2 November 2013 }}</ref> Schmeichel left Aston Villa after one season after he fell behind [[Peter Enckelman]] in the club's pecking order under new manager [[Graham Taylor]], who had replaced [[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]] in February 2002.<ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Burnton |title=Schmeichel agrees to cut short his stay at Villa |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/apr/13/newsstory.sport |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=13 April 2002 |accessdate=2 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\n====Manchester City (2002\u20132003)====\nIn 2002, Schmeichel completed a move to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=Taylor |title=Keegan captures Effenberg |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/apr/25/newsstory.sport2 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 April 2002 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/soccernet/editorial/onthemove0102.html |title=On the move \u2013 2001/2002 transfers |work=ESPN |date=31 May 2002 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> He played only one season, in 2002\u201303. Schmeichel's record in the [[Manchester derby]] is exceptional, in that he was never on the losing side. During his nine years with Manchester United, they were unbeaten against Manchester City, while in his single season with City, they won at [[Maine Road]] and drew at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man City take derby honours |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/2388563.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=9 November 2002 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Hayward |title=Goater punishes United |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2395917/Goater-punishes-United.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=10 February 2003 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nSchmeichel announced his retirement from football in April 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel announces retirement |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_city/2943837.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=13 April 2003 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Nada |last=Grkinic |title=Maine man signs off |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_city/3010663.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=11 May 2003 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1999, Schmeichel became the owner of his childhood club Hvidovre IF,<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-schmeichel-buys-copenhagen-club-1135148.html \"Schmeichel buys Copenhagen club\"]. ''[[The Independent]]''. 30 December 1999.</ref> but withdrew from the club in June 2002.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nSchmeichel worked as a pundit for the [[BBC]] after retiring, being a regular analyst on [[Match of the Day]] until 2005. He then began hosting live UEFA Champions League matches on Danish television channel [[Viasat|TV3+]], with [[Preben Elkj\u00e6r Larsen|Preben Elkj\u00e6r]] and [[Brian Laudrup]] the studio pundits. However, he still works occasionally as a pundit for the [[BBC]].\n\nHis popularity in Britain is perhaps best measured by [[Chesney Brown]] on the [[Manchester]]-based soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'', naming his former dog (a [[Great Dane]]) \"Schmeichel\".\n\nHe also took part in [[Soccer Aid]], and played for the Rest of the World team, who lost 2\u20131 after he was substituted at half-time. Schmeichel was a contestant on the 2006 series of the [[BBC]]'s popular Saturday night TV programme ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', but was voted out by the public on his 43rd birthday. He also appeared on ''[[The Weakest Link]]'' in the UK, but he was voted off as the weakest link in the first round.\n\nOn 31 August 2007, an investor group including Schmeichel announced their intention to invest 250 million DKK ([[Euro|\u20ac]]33.5 million) in the football club [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] and make him sports director. This was announced in a press conference in Danish at a hotel in [[Copenhagen]]. The offer fell through when Br\u00f8ndby failed to accept the offer within the group's deadline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penge.borsen.dk/artikel/1/115616/kursdyk_efter_broendby-nej_til_schmeichel.html|title=Kursdyk efter Br\u00f8ndby-nej til Schmeichel|first=Uffe|last=Hansen|date=3 September 2007|website=penge.borsen.dk|accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, he became the host in a new quiz, on [[TV3 (Denmark)|TV3]] named ''1 mod 100'' (the Danish version of ''[[1 vs. 100]]''). In 2008, he became the host of the European version of the [[Discovery Channel]] programme, ''[[Dirty Jobs]]''.<ref>[http://press.discovery.com/asia-pacific/dsc/programs/dirty-jobs-peter-schmeichel/ \"Dirty Jobs with Peter Schmeichel\"]. ''[[Discovery.com]]''.</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Schmeichel appeared on state owned [[Russia Today]], in a TV programme called ''The Schmeichel Show''. He received criticism from Danish media for his appearance in it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/sporten/fifavm2018/schmeichel-afviser-kritik-af-russisk-tv-program-det-drejer-sig-om-fodbold-ikke|title=Schmeichel afviser kritik af russisk tv-program: 'Det drejer sig om fodbold, ikke politik'|website=DR|accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nSchmeichel is widely regarded by pundits, as well as both former and current goalkeeping colleagues, as one of the greatest goalkeepers of all time, and also as Denmark's greatest goalkeeper ever,<ref name=\"IFFHS' Century Elections\"/><ref name=\"showstars\"/><ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"The best goalkeepers of all time\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/02/05/best.goalkeepers/index.html?eref=rss_latest|title=The best goalkeepers of all time|publisher=CNN|date=9 February 2009|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Casillas names his top ten No1s\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=949435.html|title=Casillas names his top ten No1s|publisher=UEFA.com|first=Guillem |last=Balagu\u00e9|date=5 February 2010|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Mondiali, -1\">{{cite web|url=https://sport.sky.it/calcio/mondiali/fotogallery/2014/06/02/verso_mondiale_countdown_numeri_1_panoramica_migliori.html#15|title=Mondiali, -1: da Yashin a Buffon, i portieri nella storia|publisher=Sky.it|language=Italian|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Buffon still standing\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/75977/buffon-%E2%80%98casillas-best%E2%80%99|title=Buffon: \u2018Casillas the best\u2019|publisher=Football Italia|date=19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11945/9846554/is-bayern-munichs-manuel-neuer-the-best-goalkeeper-ever|title=Is Bayern Munich's Manuel Neuer the best goalkeeper ever?|publisher=www.skysports.com|accessdate=2 November 2017|date=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/sports/soccer/blog/_/name/schaerlaeckens_leander/id/6067671/manchester-united-edwin-van-der-sar-ranks-all-greats|title=Van der Sar ranks among the all-time greats|publisher=ESPN|date=28 January 2011|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> and has been described as a modern, talented, world-class, and complete goalkeeper, who also stood out for the longevity of his career.<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"The best goalkeepers of all time\"/><ref name=\"Casillas names his top ten No1s\"/><ref name=\"Mondiali, -1\"/><ref name=\"Manchester United greatest XI\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Legends/Peter-Schmeichel.aspx|title=Peter Schmeichel|publisher=www.manutd.com|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/denmark/squad/741678.stm|title=Peter Schmeichel|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Peter Schmeichel: A profile\"/> A tall, strong and physically imposing goalkeeper, with a large frame and long reach,<ref name=\"Red11\"/><ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"The best goalkeepers of all time\"/><ref name=\"Mondiali, -1\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile\"/> as well as excellent reflexes,<ref name=\"Peter Schmeichel: A profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/15115/10037643/peter-schmeichel-a-profile|title=Peter Schmeichel: A profile of the Manchester United legend|publisher=www.skysports.com|first=Nick |last=Wright|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> he was also extremely athletic and agile for a player of his size,<ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Peter Schmeichel: A profile\"/><ref name=\"Schmeichel in Greatest XI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Features/2011/Nov/peter-schmeichel-named-goalkeeper-in-greatest-united-xi.aspx|title=Schmeichel in Greatest XI|website=ManUtd.com|first1=A.|last1=Marshall|first2=M.|last2=Shaw|date=15 November 2011|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"100 best foreign Premier League players\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/fourfourtwos-100-best-foreign-premier-league-players-ever-no9-peter-schmeichel|title=FourFourTwo's 100 best foreign Premier League players ever: No.9, Peter Schmeichel|publisher=FourFourTwo|first=Henning|last=Berg|date=10 February 2017|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"All time greats\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/5362313/Manchester-United-v-Barcelona-All-time-greats-Schmeichel-v-Zubizaretta.html|title=Manchester United v Barcelona: All time greats \u2013 Schmeichel v Zubizaretta|publisher=The Telegraph|first=Steve|last=Wilson|date=24 May 2009|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> and was known for his ability to cover the goal with his trademark \"[[star jump]]\" saves,<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/> a technique he reportedly developed from playing [[handball]].<ref name=\"Peter Schmeichel: One-on-One\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/peter-schmeichel-one-one|title=Peter Schmeichel: One-on-One|publisher=FourFourTwo|author1=Sam Pilger|date=1 August 2003|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was highly regarded for his goalkeeping technique, shot-stopping ability, and positioning between the posts, as well as his command of his area, handling, and ability to [[Goalkeeper (association football)#Sweeper-keeper|rush off his line]] both in one on one situations or when coming out to claim crosses.<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"Manchester United greatest XI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/01/29/manchester-united-players-best-11-of-all-time/peter-schmeichel-celebrating/|title=Manchester United greatest XI|publisher=The Telegraph|date=29 January 2016|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Buffon still standing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/italy/10891055/World-Cup-2014-Italy-goalkeeper-Gianluigi-Buffon-still-standing-in-Englands-way-ahead-of-clash-in-Manaus.html|title=World Cup 2014: Italy goalkeeper Gianluigi Buffon still standing in England's way ahead of clash in Manaus|website=telegraph.co.uk|publisher=The Telegraph|first=Jeremy|last=Wilson|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile\"/><ref name=\"Schmeichel in Greatest XI\"/><ref name=\"100 best foreign Premier League players\"/><ref name=\"All time greats\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/schmeichel-van-der-sar-and-casillas-inspired-me|title='Schmeichel, Van der Sar and Casillas inspired me'|publisher=www.arsenal.com|author1=Chris Harris|date=20 December 2017|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sweeper-keepers\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2145417.html |title=Sweeper-keepers: safe hands and fancy footwork |publisher=UEFA.com |author1=Paul Simpson |date=12 September 2014 |accessdate=11 November 2018 }}</ref> A courageous and fierce competitor, he was a vocal presence in goal, known for his strong character, mentality, ability to organise his defence, and leadership from the back, as well as for his criticism of his defenders whenever they made mistakes.<ref name=\"Biography\"/><ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile\"/><ref name=\"Schmeichel in Greatest XI\"/><ref name=\"100 best foreign Premier League players\"/><ref name=\"All time greats\"/> He was also effective at stopping penalties.<ref name=\"Honours\"/> In addition to his goalkeeping ability, he was also known for his capacity to read the game, as well as his adeptness with the ball at his feet, and his distribution and ability to launch swift counter-attacks with his long and accurate throws and kicks. Unusually for a goalkeeper, he would often go up for corner kicks in the opposition's area when his team were trailing, and scored 11 goals in his career.<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"Europe's goalscoring goalkeepers\"/><ref name=\"The best goalkeepers of all time\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Schmeichel in Greatest XI\"/><ref name=\"100 best foreign Premier League players\"/><ref name=\"All time greats\"/><ref name=\"Sweeper-keepers\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/900449/first-xi-goal-scoring-goalkeepers|title=Goal-scoring goalkeepers|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Robin Hackett|date=31 March 2011|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\nSource:<ref>:{{cite web|title=Schmeichel career stats|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.peter.schmeichel.9046.en.html|work=Football Database.eu|accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Schmeichel european stats|url=http://ita.worldfootball.net/spieler_profil/peter-schmeichel/2/|work=Football Database.eu|accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Club performance\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Club!!Season!!Division\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]]\n|[[1984 Danish 1st Division|1984]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Danish 1st Division|1st Division]]\n|20||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||20||0\n|-\n|[[1985 Danish 1st Division|1985]]\n|28||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||28||0\n|-\n|[[1986 Danish 2nd Division|1986]]\n|[[Danish 2nd Division|2nd Division]]\n|30||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!78!!0!! !! !!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!78!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]\n|[[1987 Danish 1st Division|1987]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Danish Superliga|1st Division]]\n|23||2|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||2\n|-\n|[[1988 Danish 1st Division|1988]]\n|26||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||0\n|-\n|[[1989 Danish 1st Division|1989]]\n|26||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||28||0\n|-\n|[[1990 Danish 1st Division|1990]]\n|26||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||28||0\n|-\n|[[1991 Danish Superliga|1991]]\n|[[Danish Superliga|Superliga]]\n|18||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||28||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!119!!2!! !! !!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!20!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!139!!2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"9\"|[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|[[1991\u201392 Manchester United F.C. season|1991\u201392]]\n|[[Football League First Division|First Division]]\n|40||0||3||0||6||0||3||0||1||0||53||0\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 Manchester United F.C. season|1992\u201393]]\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Premier League]]\n|42||0||3||0||2||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||48||0\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 Manchester United F.C. season|1993\u201394]]\n|40||0||7||0||8||0||4||0||1||0||60||0\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 Manchester United F.C. season|1994\u201395]]\n|32||0||7||0||0||0||3||0||1||0||43||0\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Manchester United F.C. season|1995\u201396]]\n|36||0||6||0||1||0||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||45||1\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 Manchester United F.C. season|1996\u201397]]\n|36||0||3||0||0||0||9||0||1||0||49||0\n|-\n|[[1997\u201398 Manchester United F.C. season|1997\u201398]]\n|32||0||4||0||0||0||7||0||1||0||44||0\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 Manchester United F.C. season|1998\u201399]]\n|34||0||8||0||0||0||13||0||1||0||56||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!292!!0!!41!!0!!17!!0!!42!!1!!6!!0!!398!!1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]]\n|[[1999\u20132000 Sporting CP season|1999\u20132000]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Primeira Liga]]\n|28||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||0\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 Primeira Liga|2000\u201301]]\n|27||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0||3||0||34||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!55!!0!!2!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!6!!0!!3!!0!!66!!0\n|-\n|[[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n|[[2001\u201302 Aston Villa F.C. season|2001\u201302]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Premier League]]\n|29||1||1||0||2||0||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||36||1\n|-\n|[[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|[[2002\u201303 Manchester City F.C. season|2002\u201303]]\n|29||0||1||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||31||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!602||3||45||0||20||0||72||1||9||0||748||4\n|}\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Denmark senior team\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1987||5||0\n|-\n|1988||11||0\n|-\n|1989||12||0\n|-\n|1990||10||0\n|-\n|1991||7||0\n|-\n|1992||12||0\n|-\n|1993||9||0\n|-\n|1994||7||0\n|-\n|1995||8||0\n|-\n|1996||10||0\n|-\n|1997||6||0\n|-\n|1998||10||0\n|-\n|1999||11||0\n|-\n|2000||10||1\n|-\n|2001||1||0\n|-\n!Total||129||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Source:<ref name=\"nftstat\">{{NFT player|id=13773|name=Peter Schmeichel|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/schmeichel-intl.html \"Peter Schmeichel \u2013 Century of International Appearances\"]. ''RSSSF''. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref>\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!# \n!Date \n!Venue\n!Opponent\n!Score\n!Result\n!Competition\n|-\n| 1 || 3 June 2000 || [[Parken Stadium]], [[Copenhagen]], Denmark || {{fb|BEL}} ||align=\"center\"| '''2'''\u20131 ||align=\"center\"| 2\u20132 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\nSource:<ref name=\"Honours\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fifa.com/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/people=57693/profile.html |title=The great Dane with the big bark |publisher=FIFA |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528082710/http://www.fifa.com/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/people=57693/profile.html |archivedate=28 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Club===\n'''Br\u00f8ndby''' \n* [[Danish 1st Division]]/[[Danish Superliga]]: [[1987 Danish 1st Division|1987]], [[1988 Danish 1st Division|1988]], [[1990 Danish 1st Division|1990]], [[1991 Danish Superliga|1991]]\n* [[Danish Cup]]: [[1989 Danish Cup|1989]]\n\n'''Manchester United''' \n* [[Premier League]]: [[1992\u201393 FA Premier League|1992\u201393]], [[1993\u201394 FA Premier League|1993\u201394]], [[1995\u201396 FA Premier League|1995\u201396]], [[1996\u201397 FA Premier League|1996\u201397]], [[1998\u201399 FA Premier League|1998\u201399]]<ref name=PL>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/307/Peter-Schmeichel/overview |title=Peter Schmeichel: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n* [[FA Cup]]: [[1993\u201394 FA Cup|1993\u201394]], [[1995\u201396 FA Cup|1995\u201396]], [[1998\u201399 FA Cup|1998\u201399]]\n* [[Football League Cup]] : [[1991\u201392 Football League Cup|1991\u201392]]\n* [[FA Charity Shield]]: [[1993 FA Charity Shield|1993]], [[1994 FA Charity Shield|1994]], [[1996 FA Charity Shield|1996]], [[1997 FA Charity Shield|1997]]\n* [[UEFA Champions League]]: [[1998\u201399 UEFA Champions League|1998\u201399]]\n* [[European Super Cup]]: [[1991 European Super Cup|1991]]\n\n'''Sporting CP''' \n* {{lang|pt|[[Primeira Liga]]|italic=no}}: [[1999\u20132000 Primeira Liga|1999\u20132000]]\n* {{lang|pt|[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]|italic=no}}: [[2000 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2000]]\n\n'''Aston Villa''' \n* [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]: [[2001 UEFA Intertoto Cup|2001]]\n\n===International===\n'''Denmark''' \n* [[UEFA European Championship]]: [[UEFA Euro 1992|1992]]<ref name=\"Honours\"/>\n\n=== Individual ===\n<!--LEAGUE AND FEDERATION-SANCTIONED AWARDS ONLY. No fan or magazine-voted awards. Listed in chronological order from last time won.-->\n* {{lang|da|[[Det Gyldne Bur]]|italic=no}} (Danish Goalkeeper of the Year): 1987, 1988, 1990, 1992\n* [[Danish Football Player of the Year]]: 1990, 1993, 1999\n* [[UEFA European Championship Team of the Tournament]]: [[UEFA Euro 1992#Awards|1992]]\n* [[Best European Goalkeeper|UEFA Goalkeeper of the Year]]: 1992, 1993, 1998\n* [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper]]: 1992, 1993<ref name=\"IFFHS' World's Best Goalkeeper of the Year\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/iffhs-gkoy.html |title=IFFHS' World's Best Goalkeeper of the Year |publisher=RSSSF |first=Jos\u00e9 Luis |last=Pierrend |date=2 February 2017 |accessdate=2 November 2017 }}</ref>\n* [[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (1990s)#FA Premier League|1992\u201393 Premier League]]\n* [[Premier League Player of the Season]]: [[1995\u201396 FA Premier League#Annual awards|1995\u201396]]<ref name=PL/>\n* [[UEFA Club Football Awards|UEFA Club Goalkeeper of the Year]]: 1997\u201398\n* UEFA Champions League 10 Seasons Dream Team (1992 to 2002): 2002\n* [[English Football Hall of Fame]]: 2003\n* [[Professional Footballers' Association|PFA]] England League Team of the Century (1907 to 2007): 2007<ref>{{cite news |title=Team of the Century: 1997\u20132007 \u2013 the Premiership's finest of the last decade |url=http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa-legends/teams-of-the-century/team-of-the-century-1997-2007 |work=GiveMeFootball.com |publisher=Give Me Football |date=5 September 2007 |accessdate=17 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021032411/http://www.givemefootball.com/pfa-legends/teams-of-the-century/team-of-the-century-1997-2007 |archivedate=21 October 2008 }}</ref>\n* [[Premier League 10 Seasons Awards]] (1992\u201393 to 2001\u201302):\n** [[Premier League 10 Seasons Awards#Teams of the Decade|Overseas and overall Team of the Decade]]\n** [[Premier League 10 Seasons Awards#Save of the Decade|Save of the Decade]] (vs. Newcastle, 21 December 1997)\n* [[Premier League 20 Seasons Awards]] (1992\u201393 to 2011\u201312):\n** [[Premier League 20 Seasons Awards#Fantasy Teams of the 20 Seasons|Fantasy Teams of the 20 Seasons]] public and panel choice\n* [[FIFA 100]]<ref name=\"Fifa 100\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/mar/04/newsstory.sport15 |title=The Fifa 100 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 March 2004 |accessdate=9 June 2015 }}</ref>\n* [[Denmark national football team#Hall of Fame|Danish Football Hall of Fame]]\n* [[World Soccer Magazine|World Soccer]]: The 100 Greatest Footballers of All Time<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/best-x-players-of-y.html#ws100 World Soccer: The 100 Greatest Footballers of All Time] Retrieved 30 December 2015</ref>\n* [[Football League 100 Legends]]\n\n==Literature==\n*{{Cite book |last=Schmeichel |first=Peter |title=Schmeichel: The Autobiography |origyear=1999 |edition=2nd |year=2000 |publisher=Virgin Publishing |location=London |isbn=0-7535-0444-8 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* [http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/1554 Danish national team profile] {{in lang|da}}\n* {{ESPN FC|8180<!-- /peter-schmeichel -->}}\n* {{Soccerway|peter-boleslaw-schmeichel/104224}}\n* [https://www.premierleague.com/players/307/Peter-Schmeichel/overview Premier League profile]\n* {{FIFA|57693}}\n* {{IMDb name|1376384}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] captain|before=[[Michael Laudrup]]|after=[[Jan Heintze]]|years=1998\u20132001}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Denmark squads\n|bg=#e11b22\n|fg=white\n|list1=\n{{Denmark squad UEFA Euro 1988}}\n{{Denmark squad UEFA Euro 1992}}\n{{Denmark squad UEFA Euro 1996}}\n{{Denmark squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Denmark squad UEFA Euro 2000}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|fg=navy\n|bg=gold\n|title=Awards\n|list1=\n{{Br\u00f8ndby IF Player of the Year}}\n{{1992\u201393 FA Premier League PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{UEFA Euro 1992 Team of the Tournament}}\n{{Danish Football Hall of Fame}}\n{{Danish Football Player of the Year}}\n{{Danish Football Goalkeeper of the Year}}\n{{Premier League Player of the Season}}\n{{Football League 100 Legends}}\n{{IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper}}\n{{Best European Goalkeeper}}\n{{UEFA Club Football Awards}}\n{{FIFA 100}}\n{{English Football Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schmeichel, Peter}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Gladsaxe Municipality]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Hvidovre IF players]]\n[[Category:Br\u00f8ndby IF players]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP footballers]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Danish 1st Division players]]\n[[Category:Danish 2nd Division players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:English Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Denmark under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1988 players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1992 players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2000 players]]\n[[Category:UEFA European Championship-winning players]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:FIFA 100]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers who have scored]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Danish television presenters]]\n[[Category:Participants in British reality television series]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Peter Schmeichel<br/><small>[[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]</small>\n| image          = Peter Schmeichel 2012-01-25 001.jpg\n| caption        = Schmeichel in 2012\n| fullname       = Peter Boles\u0142aw Schmeichel\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1963|11|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Gladsaxe Municipality|Gladsaxe]], Denmark\n| height         = 1.91 m<ref>[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/1554 Peter Schmeichel]. [[Danish Football Association|DBU]]. Retrieved 14 July 2012.</ref>\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1    = 1972\u20131975 |youthclubs1 = H\u00f8je-Gladsaxe\n| youthyears2    = 1975\u20131979 |youthclubs2 = [[BK Hero|Hero]]\n| youthyears3    = 1979\u20131981 |youthclubs3 = [[Gladsaxe-Hero BK|Gladsaxe-Hero]]\n| years1         = 1981\u20131984 |clubs1 = [[Gladsaxe-Hero BK|Gladsaxe-Hero]]           |caps1 = 46  |goals1 = 0\n| years2         = 1984\u20131987 |clubs2 = [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]]                     |caps2 = 78  |goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 1987\u20131991 |clubs3 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]                       |caps3 = 119 |goals3 = 2\n| years4         = 1991\u20131999 |clubs4 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] |caps4 = 292 |goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 1999\u20132001 |clubs5 = [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]]   |caps5 = 55  |goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 2001\u20132002 |clubs6 = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]             |caps6 = 29  |goals6 = 1\n| years7         = 2002\u20132003 |clubs7 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]     |caps7 = 29  |goals7 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 648 |totalgoals = 3<!-- LEAGUE ONLY -->\n| nationalyears1 = 1987\u20132001 |nationalteam1 = [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] |nationalcaps1 = 129 |nationalgoals1 = 1\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|DEN}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[UEFA Euro 1992|1992 Sweden]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Peter Boles\u0142aw Schmeichel''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] ({{IPA-da|\u02c8p\u02b0e\u031d\u02c0t\u0250 \u02c8smaj\u02c0kl\u0329}}; born 18 November 1963) is a Danish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], and was voted the [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper]] in 1992 and 1993. He is best remembered for his most successful years at English club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], whom he [[Captain (association football)|captained]] to victory in the [[1999 UEFA Champions League Final]] to complete [[Treble (association football)|the Treble]], and for winning [[UEFA Euro 1992]] with [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].\n\nBorn in [[Gladsaxe Municipality|Gladsaxe]], [[Copenhagen]], Schmeichel was famous for his intimidating physique\u2009\u2013\u2009at {{height|m=1.91}} tall and weighing close to {{convert|100|kg|stlb|abbr=on}} during his playing days\u2009\u2013\u2009and wore specially made size XXXL football shirts.<ref name=\"Red11\">{{cite web |title=Peter Schmeichel |url=http://www.red11.org/mufc/peter.htm |publisher=Red11.org |year=1999 |accessdate=4 November 2013 }}</ref> A fierce competitor, he was known for his loud, unstinting criticism of perceived mistakes by his defenders.<ref name=\"Biography\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2zI4AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT244|title=Manchester United: The Biography: The Complete Story of the World's Greatest Football Club|first=Jim|last=White|date=7 October 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|accessdate=4 January 2020|via=Google Books}}</ref> Unusually for a goalkeeper, Schmeichel scored 10 goals during his career, including one for the national team. He is also the most [[cap (football)|capped]] player for the Denmark national team, with 129 games between 1987 and 2001. In addition to Euro 92, he played for his country at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] and three additional [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]] tournaments. He captained the national team in 30 matches. He also represented Gladsaxe Hero, [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]], [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]], [[Sporting CP]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in a career that lasted from 1981 until 2003 and yielded 24 trophies.\n\nRegarded as one of the greatest goalkeepers of all-time, the [[IFFHS]] ranked Schmeichel among the top ten [[IFFHS World's Best Goalkeeper#Goalkeeper of the Century|keepers of the 20th century]] in 2000,<ref name=\"IFFHS' Century Elections\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/iffhs-century.html#worldkoc |title=IFFHS' Century Elections |accessdate=21 June 2007 |first=Karel |last=Stokkermans |date=30 January 2000 |work=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] }}</ref> and in 2001, Schmeichel won a public poll held by [[Reuters]], when the majority of the 200,000 participants voted him as the best goalkeeper ever, ahead of [[Lev Yashin]] and [[Gordon Banks]].<ref name=\"showstars\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showstars.dk/query:invoke/method:display/folderid:3216/lang:da/ |title=PETER SCHMEICHEL |accessdate=21 June 2007 |work=ShowStars.dk |language=Danish |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704194758/http://www.showstars.dk/query:invoke/method:display/folderid:3216/lang:da/ |archivedate=4 July 2007}}</ref> In 2003, Schmeichel was inducted into the [[English Football Hall of Fame]] in recognition of his impact on the English game. In March 2004, he was named as one of the \"125 greatest living footballers\", at the [[FIFA 100]] celebrations. His son, [[Kasper Schmeichel|Kasper]], is also a professional goalkeeper, currently playing for Premier League side [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early years===\nPeter Schmeichel was born in the [[S\u00f8borgg\u00e5rd]] parish of [[Gladsaxe Municipality|Gladsaxe]], Denmark, to Inger, a Danish nurse, and Antoni Schmeichel, a [[Polish people|Polish]] jazz musician. He held Polish [[citizen]]ship until 1970 when he, his father, and his three sisters became Danish citizens.\n\nSchmeichel inherited his middle name \u2013 Boles\u0142aw \u2013 from his great-grandfather.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), p. 25</ref> He spent his early years in the town of [[Buddinge]], [[Copenhagen]], and began his football career playing for a team in the adjacent suburb of [[H\u00f8je-Gladsaxe]]. His first match came on 7 August 1972 at the age of 8.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), p. 29</ref> After a two-and-a-half-year unbeaten run, Schmeichel was approached by BK Hero, a team from a few divisions above H\u00f8je-Gladsaxe and with one of the largest youth football schemes in Denmark. BK Hero merged with Gladsaxe BK in 1979 to form [[Gladsaxe-Hero BK]], and Schmeichel was presented with the opportunity to play for the [[Zealand Football Association|Zealand FA's]] junior representative team.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 30\u201331</ref>\n\nEventually graduating to the Gladsaxe-Hero senior squad, Schmeichel met his first mentor in [[Svend Aage Hansen]], the first team coach at the club, and later to become his father-in-law. With Gladsaxe-Hero already relegated from the Danish Third Division with three games to go, Hansen promoted Schmeichel and six others from the youth team for a match against [[IF Skjold Birker\u00f8d]]. The team lost 1\u20130, but Schmeichel received mentions in local newspapers for his personal performance.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), p. 31</ref> At the end of the season, Hansen explained to Schmeichel his plan for the future, which involved Schmeichel spending two more seasons with Gladsaxe-Hero BK before moving on to [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]], playing for the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]], and eventually having a successful career abroad. Schmeichel admits that he had received an offer to play for [[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]]'s youth team, but he turned it down as the club \"seemed a bit boring\".<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 31\u201332</ref>\n\nThe following season Gladsaxe-Hero needed only to avoid defeat to Stubbek\u00f8bing to prevent relegation from the Danish National League. In the end, Schmeichel played one of the best games of his career and Gladsaxe-Hero won the match. At the end of the game, Hansen's daughter, Bente, ran onto the pitch and hugged Schmeichel. The two ended up going out as a couple, and they eventually got married.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 32\u201333</ref>\n\nBefore becoming a professional footballer, Schmeichel had to work a number of jobs to make ends meet. His first job came in the dyeing department of a textile factory, but safety concerns led to his resignation. He then spent 12 months as a cleaner at an old people's home, before taking up an office job with the [[World Wide Fund for Nature|World Wildlife Fund]]. He originally worked in the organisation's shops, but three weeks after he joined, the store manager left and Schmeichel was promoted to the position of sales manager. Soon after, Schmeichel was called upon to do his four weeks of compulsory military service. However, this coincided with Hvidovre's summer training camp in Portugal, which he was permitted to go on with the proviso that he completed his military service the following month. Nevertheless, the delicate organisational situation that arose between the WWF, the Danish defence department and Hvidovre prompted Schmeichel to give up working for the WWF. A job with his father-in-law's flooring firm came next, until he realised that his knees could not support his {{convert|15|stone|kg}} frame for eight hours a day, and he was offered a job with the advertising firm owned by Hvidovre's chairman, Niels Erik Madsen. This was to be his last job outside football, as he was offered a contract with [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]] the following spring.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 34\u201337</ref>\n\n===Professional career===\n\n====Br\u00f8ndby (1987\u20131991)====\nDespite the fifth best defence in the league, conceding 40 goals in 30 games,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://home6.inet.tele.dk/pin/Danmarksturneringen/1985.htm |title=Danmarksturneringen 1985 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |first=Peder I. |last=Nielsen |year=1999 |publisher=Peders Fodboldstatistik |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316190707/http://home6.inet.tele.dk/pin/Danmarksturneringen/1985.htm |archivedate=16 March 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Schmeichel and Hvidovre finished in 14th place and were [[relegated]] in 1985. After only a single season, the club bounced right back to the 1st Division, but Schmeichel was lost by Hvidovre to Danish runners-up [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] before the 1987 season. Winning the Danish league in his first year, he joined a club which he helped turn into a success. He made his debut for the Danish national team in May 1987, under national manager [[Sepp Piontek]], and was selected for the [[1988 UEFA European Football Championship|Euro 88]] tournament, where he eventually became Denmark's starting goalkeeper, after initially serving as a back-up to [[Troels Rasmussen]] in Denmark's opening 3\u20132 defeat to [[Spain national football team|Spain]]; Denmark lost both of their remaining two matches 2\u20130 to [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] and [[Italy national football team|Italy]], however, and were eliminated in the first round of the competition.<ref name=\"Honours\"/>\n\nIn all, Schmeichel and Br\u00f8ndby won four championships in five seasons. The climax of his Br\u00f8ndby career would come in the European 1991 [[UEFA Cup]] competition, which saw Schmeichel as an important part of the team that reached the semi-finals, keeping seven clean sheets in the competition.<ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref name=\"Denmark's fairytale\">{{cite web|title=Euro 1992: Denmark's fairytale|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/17757335|publisher=BBC Sport|author1=Saj Chowdhury|date=12 May 2012|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> The club was eliminated from the tournament following a 2\u20131 away defeat to [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] with a last-minute goal by [[Rudi V\u00f6ller]].<ref name=\"Honours\"/> Following the tournament, Schmeichel was voted 10th in \"The World's Best Goalkeeper 1991\" poll by the [[IFFHS]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iffhs.de/?388d85ff8b00388f05e9d817285fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb8a70b |title=The World's best Goalkeeper 1991 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |publisher=IFFHS }}</ref>\n\n====Manchester United (1991\u20131999)====\n[[File:Peter Schmeichel juli 1991.JPG|thumb|Schmeichel in July 1991, just days after signing for Manchester United]]\nFollowing his showings on the international scene, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] signed Schmeichel on 6 August 1991 for \u00a3505,000,<ref>Br\u00f8ndby \u00abtabte\u00bb p\u00e5 Schmeichel, ''[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] article'', 8 August 1991</ref> a price described in 2000 by Manchester United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] as the \"bargain of the century.\"<ref name=\"mbe\">{{cite news |title=Schmeichel's MBE honour |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/1092672.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=30 December 2000 |accessdate=21 June 2007 }}</ref> It was mainly because at the time, Schmeichel was a relative unknown outside Denmark, especially within the United squad members. Schmeichel played the bulk of his career for United, eight years in total. With United, Schmeichel won five FA Premier League titles, three FA Cups, one [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], and the UEFA Champions League.\n\nManchester United finished as runners-up in Schmeichel's first season (also winning the [[Football League Cup]] for the first time in the club's history), but it was on the international stage that Schmeichel enjoyed his biggest success that year. In the Danish national team under new national manager [[Richard M\u00f8ller Nielsen]], Schmeichel was Denmark's starting goalkeeper at the [[UEFA Euro 1992|Euro 92]] tournament which they won.<ref name=\"Denmark's fairytale\"/> Although Denmark initially finished behind [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]] in their qualification campaign for the final tournament, the latter nation were banned from the competition, while Denmark replaced them in the finals.<ref name=\"Honours\"/> Schmeichel made a string of important saves during the tournament,<ref name=\"Denmark's fairytale\"/> keeping a clean sheet in Denmark's opening 0\u20130 draw against [[England national football team|England]], and producing decisive stops against [[Eric Cantona]] and [[Jean-Pierre Papin]] in a 2\u20131 win over [[France national football team|France]] to advance to the last four.<ref name=\"Honours\"/> In the semi-finals against defending champions the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], following a 2\u20132 draw after extra time, he stopped a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] from [[Marco van Basten]] \u2013 the only miss of the shoot-out \u2013 which enabled Denmark to advance to the [[UEFA Euro 1992 Final|final]] on a 5\u20134 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/24/news/24iht-bast_0.html|title=The Score From a $6 Million Soccer Star: 'Someone Had to Miss'|publisher=The New York Times|author1=Rob Hughes|date=24 June 1992|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> Schmeichel also made several decisive saves in the final, and even held a cross with one hand, keeping a clean sheet in his nation's 2\u20130 victory over Germany.<ref name=\"Schmeichel steps back in time\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1992/history-maker/index.html|title=Schmeichel steps back in time to EURO '92|publisher=UEFA.com|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1992/matches/round=217/match=6098/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Gatecrashing Denmark down Germany|publisher=UEFA.com|date=5 October 2003|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> For his performances throughout the season, he was elected \"The World's Best Goalkeeper of 1992\" by IFFHS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iffhs.de/?388d85ff8b00388f05e9d817285fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aeedb8a40b |title=The World's best Goalkeeper 1992 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |publisher=[[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]] }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393 season]], 22 [[clean sheet]]s from Schmeichel helped United win the [[Premier League]] championship, the first time the club had won England's top trophy in 26 years.<ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref name=\"The Great Dane\">{{cite web|url=https://www.unitedlounge.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=9775 |title=Schmeichel: The Great Dane|publisher=United Lounge|author1=Tom Adams|date=28 August 2009}}</ref> Schmeichel was once again named \"The World's Best Goalkeeper\" in 1993. In January 1994, Schmeichel fell out with Ferguson, as United had squandered a 3\u20130 lead to draw 3\u20133 with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. The two had a row where Schmeichel \"said the most horrible things\",<ref>\"[...] sagde de frygteligste ting.\", Schmeichel (2000), p. 143</ref> and he was subsequently sacked by Ferguson. A few days later, Schmeichel made an improvised apology to the other players. Unknown to him, Ferguson was eavesdropping on this, and he let Schmeichel stay at Manchester United.<ref name=\"mbe\"/> Schmeichel and United repeated the Premier League championship win at the end of the season, also capturing the [[FA Cup]].<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/> At international level, however, he suffered disappointment as Denmark failed to qualify for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=\"Honours\"/>\n\nSchmeichel played for Denmark at [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 96]], hosted by England. The defending European Champions went out in the preliminary group stage, despite delivering results equivalent to the Euro 92 tournament in the first round.<ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref>One victory, one draw, and one loss in three group stage matches.</ref>\n\nFollowing a match against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in November 1996, Schmeichel was accused of [[racism]] by Arsenal striker [[Ian Wright]]. During the game, Schmeichel and Wright had a number of controversies, and at the end of the game, the two players confronted each other on their way off the pitch. After the game, news emerged of a police inquiry into the incident, where it was alleged that Schmeichel had made a racist remark.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Rob |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/schmeichel-faces-racist-abuse-charge-1279851.html |title=Schmeichel faces racist abuse charge |work=The Independent |date=21 February 1997 |accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref> After months of politicising by [[The FA]] and [[The PFA]], who wanted a \"converted\" Schmeichel as their posterboy of the \"Kick Racism out of Football\" campaign, no evidence was found and the case was dropped.<ref>Schmeichel (2000), pp. 123\u2013133</ref>\n\nUnder new national manager [[Bo Johansson]], Schmeichel was a part of the Danish squad at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]. He was one of the leading members of the Danish campaign, which ended in a 3\u20132 quarter-final defeat to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref name=\"Honours\"/>\n\nSchmeichel ended his Manchester United career on [[Manchester United F.C. season 1998\u201399|the highest note]], when Schmeichel and United won [[the Treble]], the FA Premier League title, [[FA Cup]] and UEFA Champions League, in the same season. In that year's FA Cup semi-final against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], Schmeichel saved a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] by [[Dennis Bergkamp]] in the last minutes of the game (which Schmeichel revealed he was unaware of time), to send the game into extra time.<ref name=\"Honours\"/> In the absence of the suspended [[Roy Keane]], he captained United in the [[UEFA Champions League]] final in May 1999. German opponents [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] had a 1\u20130 lead until the dying minutes of the game, when United received a corner kick. Schmeichel ran into the attack attempting to cause confusion, and [[Teddy Sheringham]] scored the equalising goal. A few seconds later, [[Ole Gunnar Solskj\u00e6r]] scored the 2\u20131 winner for United to ensure that Schmeichel's United career ended on the highest possible note.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1468092.html|title=Schmeichel recalls 1999 marvel|publisher=UEFA.com|date=29 March 2010|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> In an unforgettable celebratory moment, Schmeichel was shown cartwheeling gleefully in his area after Solskj\u00e6r's winning goal.<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/>\n\nWith his departure, Manchester United had trouble finding a replacement for him, going through several high-profile goalkeepers including [[Mark Bosnich]], [[Massimo Taibi]], [[Fabien Barthez]], [[Tim Howard]] and [[Roy Carroll]] before finally buying [[Edwin van der Sar]], who Sir Alex Ferguson considered the best goalkeeper to have played for the club since Schmeichel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=396279&&cc=3888 |title=Van der Sar pens new one-year deal at United |work=[[ESPN Soccernet]] |date=15 December 2006 |accessdate=20 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nSchmeichel played his 129th and last international against Slovenia in 2001. He kept a clean sheet in the match \u2013 something he had done, staggeringly, in 42 per cent of his appearances for Manchester United. Schmeichel will be remembered as far more than being the greatest goalie in the history of De R\u00f8d-Hvide and the Red Devils. Indeed, in a 2001 Reuters poll, he beat Lev Yashin and Gordon Banks to be named the finest keeper in football history. Despite being a goalkeeper, he would run into the attack on corner kicks if his team was behind. The sight of him going up for the corner was a great distraction to opposing defenders. He scored a goal in this fashion, for Man United, in a [[1995\u201396 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] match against [[Rotor Volgograd]] at Old Trafford in September 1995. He scored in the last minutes of the game to tie the match 2\u20132, though United were eliminated from the tournament on the away goals rule.<ref name=\"Europe's goalscoring goalkeepers\"/>\n\n====Sporting CP (1999\u20132001)====\nSchmeichel decided to leave English football at the end of the 1998\u201399 season, as the gruelling 60-game season, which came with playing with a successful club, was threatening to undermine his high standards at the age of 36. Seeking a slower pace of football, he moved to [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]], where he penned a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-Man United keeper Schmeichel signs with Sporting Lisbon |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=ex-man-united-keeper-schmeichel-signs-with-sporting-lisbon-1999-06-22 |work=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=22 June 1999 |accessdate=5 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205055233/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=ex-man-united-keeper-schmeichel-signs-with-sporting-lisbon-1999-06-22 |archive-date=5 February 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his first season with the club, he won the [[1999\u20132000 Primeira Liga]] title, putting an end to the team's 18 years without a championship. He scored his only goal for the Danish national team, a penalty kick in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], in a June 2000 warm-up match for [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]].<ref name=\"Europe's goalscoring goalkeepers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2009682.html|title=Europe's goalscoring goalkeepers|publisher=UEFA.com|date=9 July 2014|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref> He represented Denmark at Euro 2000, where the team was eliminated in the group stage. He announced his retirement from the national team in February 2001,<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel calls time on Denmark |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/football/europe/newsid_1180000/1180695.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 February 2001 |accessdate=2 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010717145503/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/football/europe/newsid_1180000/1180695.stm |archivedate=17 July 2001 }}</ref> and played his final match (his 129th international appearance)<ref name=\"Honours\"/> two months later, captaining the side in a 3\u20130 friendly win over [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] at Copenhagen's [[Parken Stadium]]; he was substituted in the 65th minute to a standing ovation, replaced by long-time back-up [[Peter Kj\u00e6r (footballer)|Peter Kj\u00e6r]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel bows out |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/2001/04/25/denmark_slovenia/ |work=CNNSI.com |publisher=CNN/Sports Illustrated |date=25 April 2001 |accessdate=2 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103231945/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/2001/04/25/denmark_slovenia/ |archive-date=3 November 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHis second year with Sporting was remarkable in that it was the first time in 14 years, since his Hvidovre days, that Schmeichel's club had finished below second place in the league. Schmeichel stated his wish to activate a contract option of a further year at Sporting in January 2001,<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel staying at Sporting |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1114009.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=12 January 2001 |accessdate=2 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010820055107/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/football/europe/newsid_1114000/1114009.stm |archivedate=20 August 2001 }}</ref> but eventually decided to leave the club when his contract expired in June 2001.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel leaves Sporting Lisbon |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1391019.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=15 June 2001 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113032429/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1391019.stm |archivedate=13 January 2009 }}</ref>\n\n====Aston Villa (2001\u20132002)====\nSchmeichel returned to England with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in July 2001, signing a one-year contract with the option to extend it by a further year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Villa clinch Schmeichel deal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/1435755.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=12 July 2001 |accessdate=21 June 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030418154533/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/1435755.stm |archivedate=18 April 2003 }}</ref> On 20 October 2001, Schmeichel became the first goalkeeper to score a Premier League goal, in a 3\u20132 defeat away to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]];<ref name=\"Honours\"/> this feat has been repeated only four times: by [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]' [[Brad Friedel]] on 21 February 2004, also from a corner kick; by [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]'s [[Paul Robinson (goalkeeper)|Paul Robinson]] from a free-kick on 17 March 2007; by Everton's [[Tim Howard]] on 4 January 2012; and by [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]'s [[Asmir Begovi\u0107]] on 2 November 2013.<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=McKenna |title=Stoke 1\u20131 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24681360 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=2 November 2013 |accessdate=2 November 2013 }}</ref> Schmeichel left Aston Villa after one season after he fell behind [[Peter Enckelman]] in the club's pecking order under new manager [[Graham Taylor]], who had replaced [[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]] in February 2002.<ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Burnton |title=Schmeichel agrees to cut short his stay at Villa |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/apr/13/newsstory.sport |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=13 April 2002 |accessdate=2 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\n====Manchester City (2002\u20132003)====\nIn 2002, Schmeichel completed a move to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=Taylor |title=Keegan captures Effenberg |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/apr/25/newsstory.sport2 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 April 2002 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/soccernet/editorial/onthemove0102.html |title=On the move \u2013 2001/2002 transfers |work=ESPN |date=31 May 2002 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> He played only one season, in 2002\u201303. Schmeichel's record in the [[Manchester derby]] is exceptional, in that he was never on the losing side. During his nine years with Manchester United, they were unbeaten against Manchester City, while in his single season with City, they won at [[Maine Road]] and drew at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man City take derby honours |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/2388563.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=9 November 2002 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Hayward |title=Goater punishes United |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2395917/Goater-punishes-United.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=10 February 2003 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nSchmeichel announced his retirement from football in April 2003.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schmeichel announces retirement |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_city/2943837.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=13 April 2003 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Nada |last=Grkinic |title=Maine man signs off |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_city/3010663.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=11 May 2003 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 1999, Schmeichel became the owner of his childhood club Hvidovre IF,<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-schmeichel-buys-copenhagen-club-1135148.html \"Schmeichel buys Copenhagen club\"]. ''[[The Independent]]''. 30 December 1999.</ref> but withdrew from the club in June 2002.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}\n\nSchmeichel worked as a pundit for the [[BBC]] after retiring, being a regular analyst on [[Match of the Day]] until 2005. He then began hosting live UEFA Champions League matches on Danish television channel [[Viasat|TV3+]], with [[Preben Elkj\u00e6r Larsen|Preben Elkj\u00e6r]] and [[Brian Laudrup]] the studio pundits. However, he still works occasionally as a pundit for the [[BBC]].\n\nHis popularity in Britain is perhaps best measured by [[Chesney Brown]] on the [[Manchester]]-based soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'', naming his former dog (a [[Great Dane]]) \"Schmeichel\".\n\nHe also took part in [[Soccer Aid]], and played for the Rest of the World team, who lost 2\u20131 after he was substituted at half-time. Schmeichel was a contestant on the 2006 series of the [[BBC]]'s popular Saturday night TV programme ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', but was voted out by the public on his 43rd birthday. He also appeared on ''[[The Weakest Link]]'' in the UK, but he was voted off as the weakest link in the first round.\n\nOn 31 August 2007, an investor group including Schmeichel announced their intention to invest 250 million DKK ([[Euro|\u20ac]]33.5 million) in the football club [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] and make him sports director. This was announced in a press conference in Danish at a hotel in [[Copenhagen]]. The offer fell through when Br\u00f8ndby failed to accept the offer within the group's deadline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://penge.borsen.dk/artikel/1/115616/kursdyk_efter_broendby-nej_til_schmeichel.html|title=Kursdyk efter Br\u00f8ndby-nej til Schmeichel|first=Uffe|last=Hansen|date=3 September 2007|website=penge.borsen.dk|accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, he became the host in a new quiz, on [[TV3 (Denmark)|TV3]] named ''1 mod 100'' (the Danish version of ''[[1 vs. 100]]''). In 2008, he became the host of the European version of the [[Discovery Channel]] programme, ''[[Dirty Jobs]]''.<ref>[http://press.discovery.com/asia-pacific/dsc/programs/dirty-jobs-peter-schmeichel/ \"Dirty Jobs with Peter Schmeichel\"]. ''[[Discovery.com]]''.</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Schmeichel appeared on state owned [[Russia Today]], in a TV programme called ''The Schmeichel Show''. He received criticism from Danish media for his appearance in it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/sporten/fifavm2018/schmeichel-afviser-kritik-af-russisk-tv-program-det-drejer-sig-om-fodbold-ikke|title=Schmeichel afviser kritik af russisk tv-program: 'Det drejer sig om fodbold, ikke politik'|website=DR|accessdate=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nSchmeichel is widely regarded by pundits, as well as both former and current goalkeeping colleagues, as one of the greatest goalkeepers of all time, and also as Denmark's greatest goalkeeper ever,<ref name=\"IFFHS' Century Elections\"/><ref name=\"showstars\"/><ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"The best goalkeepers of all time\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/02/05/best.goalkeepers/index.html?eref=rss_latest|title=The best goalkeepers of all time|publisher=CNN|date=9 February 2009|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Casillas names his top ten No1s\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=949435.html|title=Casillas names his top ten No1s|publisher=UEFA.com|first=Guillem |last=Balagu\u00e9|date=5 February 2010|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Mondiali, -1\">{{cite web|url=https://sport.sky.it/calcio/mondiali/fotogallery/2014/06/02/verso_mondiale_countdown_numeri_1_panoramica_migliori.html#15|title=Mondiali, -1: da Yashin a Buffon, i portieri nella storia|publisher=Sky.it|language=Italian|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Buffon still standing\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/75977/buffon-%E2%80%98casillas-best%E2%80%99|title=Buffon: \u2018Casillas the best\u2019|publisher=Football Italia|date=19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11945/9846554/is-bayern-munichs-manuel-neuer-the-best-goalkeeper-ever|title=Is Bayern Munich's Manuel Neuer the best goalkeeper ever?|publisher=www.skysports.com|accessdate=2 November 2017|date=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/sports/soccer/blog/_/name/schaerlaeckens_leander/id/6067671/manchester-united-edwin-van-der-sar-ranks-all-greats|title=Van der Sar ranks among the all-time greats|publisher=ESPN|date=28 January 2011|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> and has been described as a modern, talented, world-class, and complete goalkeeper, who also stood out for the longevity of his career.<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"The best goalkeepers of all time\"/><ref name=\"Casillas names his top ten No1s\"/><ref name=\"Mondiali, -1\"/><ref name=\"Manchester United greatest XI\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Legends/Peter-Schmeichel.aspx|title=Peter Schmeichel|publisher=www.manutd.com|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/denmark/squad/741678.stm|title=Peter Schmeichel|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Peter Schmeichel: A profile\"/> A tall, strong and physically imposing goalkeeper, with a large frame and long reach,<ref name=\"Red11\"/><ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"The best goalkeepers of all time\"/><ref name=\"Mondiali, -1\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile\"/> as well as excellent reflexes,<ref name=\"Peter Schmeichel: A profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/15115/10037643/peter-schmeichel-a-profile|title=Peter Schmeichel: A profile of the Manchester United legend|publisher=www.skysports.com|first=Nick |last=Wright|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> he was also extremely athletic and agile for a player of his size,<ref name=\"Honours\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Peter Schmeichel: A profile\"/><ref name=\"Schmeichel in Greatest XI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Features/2011/Nov/peter-schmeichel-named-goalkeeper-in-greatest-united-xi.aspx|title=Schmeichel in Greatest XI|website=ManUtd.com|first1=A.|last1=Marshall|first2=M.|last2=Shaw|date=15 November 2011|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"100 best foreign Premier League players\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/fourfourtwos-100-best-foreign-premier-league-players-ever-no9-peter-schmeichel|title=FourFourTwo's 100 best foreign Premier League players ever: No.9, Peter Schmeichel|publisher=FourFourTwo|first=Henning|last=Berg|date=10 February 2017|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"All time greats\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-united/5362313/Manchester-United-v-Barcelona-All-time-greats-Schmeichel-v-Zubizaretta.html|title=Manchester United v Barcelona: All time greats \u2013 Schmeichel v Zubizaretta|publisher=The Telegraph|first=Steve|last=Wilson|date=24 May 2009|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> and was known for his ability to cover the goal with his trademark \"[[star jump]]\" saves,<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/> a technique he reportedly developed from playing [[handball]].<ref name=\"Peter Schmeichel: One-on-One\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/peter-schmeichel-one-one|title=Peter Schmeichel: One-on-One|publisher=FourFourTwo|author1=Sam Pilger|date=1 August 2003|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was highly regarded for his goalkeeping technique, shot-stopping ability, and positioning between the posts, as well as his command of his area, handling, and ability to [[Goalkeeper (association football)#Sweeper-keeper|rush off his line]] both in one on one situations or when coming out to claim crosses.<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"Manchester United greatest XI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/01/29/manchester-united-players-best-11-of-all-time/peter-schmeichel-celebrating/|title=Manchester United greatest XI|publisher=The Telegraph|date=29 January 2016|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Buffon still standing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/italy/10891055/World-Cup-2014-Italy-goalkeeper-Gianluigi-Buffon-still-standing-in-Englands-way-ahead-of-clash-in-Manaus.html|title=World Cup 2014: Italy goalkeeper Gianluigi Buffon still standing in England's way ahead of clash in Manaus|website=telegraph.co.uk|publisher=The Telegraph|first=Jeremy|last=Wilson|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile\"/><ref name=\"Schmeichel in Greatest XI\"/><ref name=\"100 best foreign Premier League players\"/><ref name=\"All time greats\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/schmeichel-van-der-sar-and-casillas-inspired-me|title='Schmeichel, Van der Sar and Casillas inspired me'|publisher=www.arsenal.com|author1=Chris Harris|date=20 December 2017|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sweeper-keepers\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2145417.html |title=Sweeper-keepers: safe hands and fancy footwork |publisher=UEFA.com |author1=Paul Simpson |date=12 September 2014 |accessdate=11 November 2018 }}</ref> A courageous and fierce competitor, he was a vocal presence in goal, known for his strong character, mentality, ability to organise his defence, and leadership from the back, as well as for his criticism of his defenders whenever they made mistakes.<ref name=\"Biography\"/><ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Euro 2000 Profile\"/><ref name=\"Schmeichel in Greatest XI\"/><ref name=\"100 best foreign Premier League players\"/><ref name=\"All time greats\"/> He was also effective at stopping penalties.<ref name=\"Honours\"/> In addition to his goalkeeping ability, he was also known for his capacity to read the game, as well as his adeptness with the ball at his feet, and his distribution and ability to launch swift counter-attacks with his long and accurate throws and kicks. Unusually for a goalkeeper, he would often go up for corner kicks in the opposition's area when his team were trailing, and scored 11 goals in his career.<ref name=\"The Great Dane\"/><ref name=\"Europe's goalscoring goalkeepers\"/><ref name=\"The best goalkeepers of all time\"/><ref name=\"manutd-legends-Schmeichel\"/><ref name=\"Schmeichel in Greatest XI\"/><ref name=\"100 best foreign Premier League players\"/><ref name=\"All time greats\"/><ref name=\"Sweeper-keepers\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/900449/first-xi-goal-scoring-goalkeepers|title=Goal-scoring goalkeepers|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Robin Hackett|date=31 March 2011|accessdate=3 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\nSource:<ref>:{{cite web|title=Schmeichel career stats|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.peter.schmeichel.9046.en.html|work=Football Database.eu|accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Schmeichel european stats|url=http://ita.worldfootball.net/spieler_profil/peter-schmeichel/2/|work=Football Database.eu|accessdate=14 July 2012}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Club performance\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Club!!Season!!Division\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n!Apps!!Goals\n